# ── Line endings ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Normalize all text to LF in the repository AND check out LF everywhere (2026-07-11; mirrors
# clusterio-docker 984a5fc). Checkout-native (autocrlf) was tried first and produced constant
# churn: every automated tool (agents, Node scripts) writes LF against a CRLF working tree,
# accumulating mixed-ending files and defeating exact-string edits. The index was already all-LF,
# so this changes CHECKOUT ONLY — no content rewrite. After pulling this, refresh your clone:
#   git config core.autocrlf false && git rm -rf --cached . -q && git reset --hard
# Windows-only script types below still check out CRLF (later rules win).
* text=auto eol=lf

# Scripts executed inside Linux containers MUST stay LF even on Windows checkouts
# (a CRLF shebang or line-continuation breaks bash and Docker builds).
*.sh   text eol=lf
*.bash text eol=lf

# Windows-only helper scripts keep CRLF.
*.ps1 text eol=crlf
*.cmd text eol=crlf
*.bat text eol=crlf

# Binary assets — never normalize or diff as text.
*.zip   binary
*.png   binary
*.jpg   binary
*.jpeg  binary
*.gif   binary
*.ico   binary
*.woff  binary
*.woff2 binary

# ── CI Docker assets ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The working tree is otherwise CRLF (Windows dev), but these files are consumed on Linux.
# A CRLF Dockerfile breaks `RUN ... \` line continuations during the Docker build, so force
# LF for the CI Docker/compose assets regardless of local autocrlf settings.
docker/ci/Dockerfile.factorio-baked text eol=lf
docker-compose.ci.yml text eol=lf
